Yes ‚Äî you **can extend the JupyterLab file browser** to show `/mnt/gcs` as a separate sidebar browser **with its own tab**.

Here‚Äôs a high-level overview of what you need to do, followed by concrete code to get you started.

---

## ‚úÖ Goal

Create a **custom file browser panel** in JupyterLab‚Äôs sidebar that points to a **read-only local directory** like `/mnt/gcs`.

---

## üîß Approach

1. **Extend `@jupyterlab/filebrowser`** with a new `FileBrowser` instance.
2. Use a **custom `FileBrowser` ID** to avoid clashing with the default.
3. Mount it to a **sidebar tab** with a custom icon and label.
4. Optionally disable uploads and deletions to make it read-only.

---

## üß™ Minimal Example: Custom File Browser Sidebar (for `/mnt/gcs`)

### `index.ts` for a new JupyterLab extension

```ts
import {
  JupyterFrontEnd, JupyterFrontEndPlugin
} from '@jupyterlab/application';

import {
  IFileBrowserFactory, FileBrowser
} from '@jupyterlab/filebrowser';

import { Widget } from '@lumino/widgets';

const GcsBrowserPlugin: JupyterFrontEndPlugin<void> = {
  id: 'gcs-browser',
  autoStart: true,
  requires: [IFileBrowserFactory],
  activate: (app: JupyterFrontEnd, factory: IFileBrowserFactory) => {
    console.log('GCS File Browser extension activated');

    // Create a new FileBrowser instance pointing to /mnt/gcs
    const gcsBrowser = new FileBrowser('gcs-file-browser', {
      ...factory,
      commands: app.commands,
    });

    // Navigate to the read-only directory
    void gcsBrowser.model.restored.then(() => {
      void gcsBrowser.model.cd('/mnt/gcs');
    });

    // Add to sidebar
    gcsBrowser.title.iconClass = 'jp-FolderIcon';
    gcsBrowser.title.caption = 'GCS Files';
    app.shell.add(gcsBrowser, 'left', { rank: 101 });
  }
};

export default GcsBrowserPlugin;
```

---

## üîê Optional: Make it Read-Only (UI Only)

To make the file browser **visually read-only**:
```ts
gcsBrowser.toolbar.node.querySelector('[title="Upload Files"]').remove();
// Hide other actions or override commands to be no-ops
```

To make it **truly read-only**, you should mount `/mnt/gcs` as read-only with `gcsfuse` (you've already planned this).

---

## üß± Build Instructions

Make sure your `package.json` declares dependencies like:

```json
"dependencies": {
  "@jupyterlab/application": "^4.0.0",
  "@jupyterlab/filebrowser": "^4.0.0",
  "@jupyterlab/apputils": "^4.0.0"
}
```

Then compile and link the extension:

```bash
jlpm install
jlpm build
jupyter labextension link .
```

---

## üß† Tip: You can also use a custom icon

To use a custom icon:
```ts
import { LabIcon } from '@jupyterlab/ui-components';
import gcsSvg from '../style/gcs-icon.svg';

const gcsIcon = new LabIcon({
  name: 'custom:gcs-icon',
  svgstr: gcsSvg
});

gcsBrowser.title.icon = gcsIcon;
```

